Brexit, and then?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for the United Kingdom, Europe, and the world at large to digest the implications of the 'Brexit' referendum conducted by the United Kingdom.
The deepest consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the United Kingdom's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not "cut the branch it was sitting on": after all, an amicable divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as often happens – could become complicated.
The benefits of commercial and economic integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU took seriously its conviction that further economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the links remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
However, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes for companies in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, seems to be taking a hard line: "Out means out," he said.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first step of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that in order to deter other countries from leaving, the EU should accept no compromise, offering the United Kingdom little more than what the World Trade Organization agreements guarantee it.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the benefits it offers to its members, which far exceed its costs.
Economic prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and the pride of being a European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that is nonetheless clear, both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the Republican primary elections in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the past four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that trade agreements are the source of their troubles.
Although this is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of business interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
Not surprisingly, the results were one-way: the workers' negotiating position has weakened further, thereby exacerbating the effects of legislation that reduce the power of unions and employees' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
Intellectual property rules, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
However, any increase in the market power of businesses implicitly means a decrease in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and declining real wages have been added to those of austerity, which has threatened compressions in public services that many low- and middle-income workers depend on.
The economic uncertainty resulting for workers, combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for everyone, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads – as long as we are in the presence of normal negatively sloped demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
This is especially worrisome in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high global unemployment rate.
Europe, particularly the euro zone, has been very poorly managed over the past decades, to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that countries that have successfully reduced unemployment will inevitably end up taking more refugees than their fair share.
Workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a cheaper workforce.
The burden of refugees, unsurprisingly, is borne by those who are least able to do so.
Of course, there is a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social protection, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and compressions in public services has been the evisceration of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Households in the middle class and the working class have not benefited from economic growth.
They know that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions devoted to saving the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real (inflation-adjusted) median income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should not come as a surprise.
Moreover, politicians who promised change did not meet expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew that the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing what little trust they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to correct it.
This is also understandable: new politicians shared the perspectives of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for all.
However, a vote of anger does not solve the problems, and may even lead to a worse political and economic situation.
It is the same if one responds to a vote with anger.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment has been able to do so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider improving the well-being of ordinary citizens as its primary objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing means and ends: for example, free trade, if managed well, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if managed poorly, it will certainly reduce the standard of living for many – perhaps most – citizens.
There are alternatives to current neoliberal arrangements that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership with the EU proposed by US President Barack Obama – that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the former and avoid the latter.
